<methodology slug="perf-test-tools">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>dev</group>
    <domain>automation-tooling</domain>
    <summary>Load and stress testing using k6 and Locust with CI/CD performance gates that block PRs introducing latency regressions.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>performance-testing</tag>
      <tag>load-testing</tag>
      <tag>k6</tag>
      <tag>locust</tag>
      <tag>ci-gates</tag>
      <tag>threshold-monitoring</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>Performance Testing Tools: k6 and Locust</title>

    <summary>Load and stress testing using k6 (JavaScript, single binary) and Locust (Python, web UI), with CI/CD performance gates that block PRs introducing latency regressions. The concrete rule: run a 30-second smoke at 5 VUs before any real test — if smoke fails, fix the script, not the system under test.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Without baseline perf tests, latency regressions slip into production undetected. k6 and Locust model realistic user behavior (weighted scenarios, think time, staged ramps) and emit structured JSON output that CI can diff against baselines. The p(95)&lt;500ms, error_rate&lt;1% threshold pattern is the minimum gate; tighter thresholds must be validated over multiple runs before being added to CI gate.</p>
      <p>k6 and Locust replace manual load-test attempts with reproducible, version-controlled scenarios that agents can generate, run, and integrate into the CI pipeline. Structured output enables regression detection and trend analysis across commits.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Establishing a baseline load test for a new HTTP API before first production rollout.</item>
        <item>Adding CI perf gates that block PRs introducing more than 10% latency regression.</item>
        <item>Capacity planning: finding the knee by ramping VUs at increasing targets.</item>
        <item>Reproducing a production incident with a scripted realistic scenario.</item>
        <item>Comparing two implementations (rewrite, ORM swap) under identical synthetic load.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Functional bugs — perf tools don't surface logic errors, just timing/throughput.</item>
        <item>Frontend UX perf — use Lighthouse, WebPageTest, Playwright tracing instead.</item>
        <item>Pre-MVP products with no defined SLOs — you'll measure noise.</item>
        <item>Single-shot benchmarks of pure functions — use pytest-benchmark / vitest bench.</item>
        <item>Tests against shared staging environments — results are unreproducible due to neighbour load.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="smoke-first-rule">
      <p>Always run a 30-second smoke test at 5 VUs before any real load test. If smoke fails, fix the script before touching the system under test.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always run a 30-second smoke test at 5 VUs before any real load test. If smoke fails, fix the script before touching the system under test.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents that skip smoke tests waste 30 minutes of real load runs on a broken script. Smoke at 5 VUs confirms authentication works, scenarios parse, and all HTTP routes respond — the minimum correctness check.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="k6-patterns">
      <p>Scripting patterns for k6 (JavaScript) with staged ramp configuration, threshold setup, and CI integration.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>In k6, always export raw JSON (--out json=results.json) for trend analysis; HTML reports are throwaway. Pin tool version in CI (grafana/k6:0.50.0) — minor versions change metric names.</statement>
        <rationale>JSON output enables diffing runs across commits. Unpinned versions produce metric name mismatches that silently break threshold checks.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>k6 is JavaScript but does not support Node.js APIs. Do not import fs, axios, or node built-ins — they don't exist in k6's runtime.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents hallucinate k6 module names (k6/http2 doesn't exist). Run k6 inspect script.js before any real run to catch import errors.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use standard threshold pattern: http_req_duration p(95) &lt; 500ms, http_req_failed rate &lt; 1%, custom errorRate &lt; 5%.</statement>
        <rationale>These thresholds should be validated over 3+ baseline runs before adding to CI gate. Too-tight thresholds cause flakes that erode trust.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use standard stage pattern: 2m ramp to 50 VUs, 5m hold, 2m ramp to 100 VUs, 5m hold, 2m ramp down.</statement>
        <rationale>Staged ramps warm up the system gradually and reveal capacity at different load levels.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="locust-patterns">
      <p>Scripting patterns for Locust (Python) with weighted tasks, auth setup, and custom metrics.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>In Locust, always use self.client for HTTP calls — never use the requests library directly. Calls via requests are invisible to Locust's measurement layer.</statement>
        <rationale>Invisible requests produce false-negative results: the scenario runs but Locust shows no requests in the dashboard or output.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run headless: locust -f locustfile.py --headless -u 100 -r 10 -t 5m</statement>
        <rationale>Headless mode is appropriate for CI; web UI is for interactive exploration.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use @task(N) weight to model realistic user behavior (browse 10x more than checkout 1x).</statement>
        <rationale>Weighted tasks produce realistic request distributions that match production traffic patterns.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="think-time-rule">
      <p>Always include realistic think time in scenarios. Without think time, you benchmark the load generator, not the SUT.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always include realistic think time in scenarios: sleep(random(1, 4)) in k6, between(1, 5) in Locust. Without think time, you benchmark the load generator, not the SUT.</statement>
        <rationale>Real users don't fire requests as fast as possible. Scenarios without think time produce artificially high request rates that break before revealing actual capacity limits.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ci-integration">
      <p>Wire load tests into CI with structured JSON output and threshold gates that block PRs on regression.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="distributed-load">
      <p>Local laptop runs are CPU-bound on the load generator before the SUT reaches capacity. Use distributed mode past ~500 RPS: k6 cloud (grafana/k6-cloud), Locust master/worker setup. Tag all runs with git SHA and scenario name in metric labels for trend analysis.</p>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>Step 1: Agent reads OpenAPI spec or route table and generates a weighted scenario file (k6 or Locust). Step 2: Agent runs a 30-second smoke at 5 VUs to confirm script correctness. Step 3: If smoke passes, agent runs the staged ramp. Step 4: Agent publishes JSON output for a review agent to compare against baseline.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always smoke-test the generated script first. Agents that go straight to 1000 VUs waste cloud spend when the scenario is broken.</statement>
        <rationale>A broken scenario at 1000 VUs costs real money and time. A smoke at 5 VUs costs 30 seconds.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="critical-gotchas">
      <p>Common failure modes when agents generate and run load tests.</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent copies BASE_URL hardcoded to production.</description>
        <reason>Force __ENV.BASE_URL in k6 and fail the script if unset. This prevents accidental load against prod.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>check() missing from k6 scenarios.</description>
        <reason>Without check() + errorRate.add(1), the threshold output reads success even when the SUT is 5xx-ing. check() is mandatory for every response.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent auto-tunes thresholds based on previous run results.</description>
        <reason>Convergence on the regressed value — the threshold degrades to match the slow system instead of catching the regression.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Thresholds set too tight in CI (p95 &lt; 200ms on staging).</description>
        <reason>Flakes that erode trust cause teams to relax all thresholds. Set realistic thresholds validated over 3+ runs before adding to CI gate.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Combining soak tests (8h, low load) and stress tests (3 min, ramp to break) into one scenario.</description>
        <reason>Agents conflate them. Soak finds memory leaks and connection pool exhaustion; stress finds throughput ceiling. Keep them in separate files.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs hallucinate k6 modules (k6/http2 doesn't exist).</description>
        <reason>Always run k6 inspect script.js before a real run to catch import errors.</reason>
      </antipattern>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Locust agents use requests instead of self.client.</description>
        <reason>Calls via requests are invisible to Locust's measurement layer and won't be counted.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="human-in-loop-checkpoint">
      <p>Review generated scenarios before running tests longer than 5 minutes to prevent cloud spend waste.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Review the generated scenario weights and stage shape before running any test lasting more than 5 minutes. Cloud spend accumulates quickly at 100+ VUs.</statement>
        <rationale>An agent that starts a 30-minute k6 cloud run with wrong weights or wrong target URL burns budget and produces useless data. The 30-second review before the run is the cheapest gate.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="soak-vs-stress">
      <p>Keep soak tests (8h, low load) and stress tests (3 min, ramp to break) in separate files with different configurations.</p>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Keep soak tests (8h, low load) and stress tests (3 min, ramp to break) in separate files. Never combine into one scenario.</statement>
        <rationale>Agents conflate them. Soak finds memory leaks and connection pool exhaustion; stress finds throughput ceiling. They require different VU counts, durations, and thresholds.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-reference">
      <p>Tool ecosystem for load and performance testing.</p>

      <list>
        <item>k6: modern JS load testing, single binary. brew install k6 / docker grafana/k6</item>
        <item>locust: Python load testing with web UI. pip install locust</item>
        <item>wrk / wrk2: low-overhead HTTP benchmarking. apt install wrk</item>
        <item>vegeta: constant-rate Go HTTP attacker. go install github.com/tsenart/vegeta/v12@latest</item>
        <item>pytest-benchmark: Python micro-benchmarks with regression alerts. pip install pytest-benchmark</item>
        <item>hyperfine: CLI command benchmark with stats. cargo install hyperfine</item>
        <item>oha: Rust wrk alternative with TUI. cargo install oha</item>
        <item>bombardier: Fast Go HTTP benchmarking. go install github.com/codesenberg/bombardier@latest</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="saas-services">
      <p>Hosted performance testing and monitoring services for distributed load and trend analysis.</p>

      <list>
        <item>Grafana k6 Cloud: Distributed VUs, dashboards, REST API. k6 cloud CLI integration.</item>
        <item>Locust Cloud: Hosted Locust workers via CLI.</item>
        <item>Artillery: YAML scenarios + CLI, good for multi-tenant SaaS tests.</item>
        <item>Gatling Enterprise: Scala DSL, heavier learning curve for agents.</item>
        <item>BlazeMeter: JMeter compatible, REST API.</item>
        <item>Datadog Synthetics + APM: Tie load runs to APM traces and distributed traces.</item>
        <item>GitHub Actions grafana/k6-action: One-line CI integration for k6.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices-summary">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run a 30-second smoke at 5 VUs before any real test. If smoke fails, fix the script — not the SUT.</statement>
        <rationale>Smoke testing is the minimal correctness check and prevents wasted time on broken scenarios.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always export raw JSON (--out json=) for diffing across runs; HTML reports are throwaway.</statement>
        <rationale>JSON enables regression detection and trend analysis. HTML reports are used once and discarded.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use realistic think time and keep-alive on; without them you're benchmarking the load generator.</statement>
        <rationale>Real users have think time between requests; connection pooling is standard in production.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Separate "soak" (8h, low load) from "stress" (3 min, ramp to break) into distinct files; agents conflate them.</statement>
        <rationale>Soak and stress test different failure modes and require different configurations.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Tag runs with git SHA + scenario name in metric labels — required for trend analysis.</statement>
        <rationale>Trend analysis requires identifying which commit produced which results.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Pin tool versions in CI (grafana/k6:0.50.0) — k6 minor versions change metric names.</statement>
        <rationale>Version drift causes silent metric name mismatches that break threshold checks.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/k6-test.js" purpose="k6 scenario with staged ramp, thresholds, and weighted scenario functions."/>
      <template path="templates/locustfile.py" purpose="Locust scenario with weighted tasks, auth setup, and custom metrics."/>
      <template path="templates/check-perf.py" purpose="CI threshold checker: fail if p95 or error rate exceeds limits from JSON results."/>
      <template path="templates/performance.yml" purpose="GitHub Actions workflow running k6 gate + pytest benchmarks."/>
    </templates>

